import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px
! pip install dash
from dash import Dash, dcc, html, Input, Output
import numpy as np
from google.colab import drive
drive.mount('/content/drive')
# World Coverage: beginning

# The table that describes which type of coverage is typical or not for each continent in 2001-2021. Soon will help us to understand the connection between climat and the
# fenomenon of natural fires.
world_c1 = pd.read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ansstey/fires/main/WorldCover1.csv')
# Some of data rows in column 'Item' here are empty everywhere, so we can delete ones.
world_c1.dropna(inplace=True, axis=0)
# The graph which describes natural plant coverage in the world in general in 2001-2021.
world_c1_gen = world_c1.query("`Area` == 'World'")
fig1_c1 = px.bar(data_frame=world_c1_gen, x='Value', y='Item', animation_frame='Year', animation_group='Item', color='Item', range_x=[0, 6e6])
fig1_c1.show()
# The values have not changed that much in 20 years. It is seen that Earth is mostly covered with forests and grasslands. And we can say that they occur in most of climatic zones.
# Analysis of natural coverage in Europe
As we can see on the graf, the Europe is mostly covered with forests. And the area covered with forests is still growing surprisingly.

world_c1_eu = world_c1.query("`Area` == 'Europe'")
fig1_c1_eu = px.bar(data_frame=world_c1_eu, x='Value', y='Item', animation_frame='Year', animation_group='Item', color='Item', range_x=[0, 1.4e6])
fig1_c1_eu.show()

#Analysis of natural coverage in Asia
*  Here the situation is different. Barren lands are typical for Asia and are dominant along with grasslands. Barren land is typically a land poor for minerals and water and is not capable of growing crops on it.
* On the other hand, the grasslands became dominant during the last few years, which is a sign of climate change. 🌻

world_c1_as = world_c1.query("`Area` == 'Asia'")
fig1_c1_as = px.bar(data_frame=world_c1_as, x='Value', y='Item', animation_frame='Year', animation_group='Item', color='Item', range_x=[0, 1e6])
fig1_c1_as.show()

#Analysis of natural coverage in North America
*   In North America permament snow glaciers are abundant, especially near the North pole.
*   Forests are dominant which is not unique in general.

world_c1_na = world_c1.query("`Area` == 'Northern America'")
fig1_c1_na = px.bar(data_frame=world_c1_na, x='Value', y='Item', animation_frame='Year', animation_group='Item', color='Item', range_x=[0, 1e6])
fig1_c1_na.show()
#Analysis of natural coverage in South America

world_c1_sa = world_c1.query("`Area` == 'South America'")
fig1_c1_sa = px.bar(data_frame=world_c1_sa, x='Value', y='Item', animation_frame='Year', animation_group='Item', color='Item', range_x=[0, 1.2e6])
fig1_c1_sa.show()

#Analysis of natural coverage in Africa

*   The barren lands are dominant, which is clear, as the biggest desert on Earth, the Sahara desert, is located in Africa.
*   Tree-covered are also abundant, escpecially in the central Africa (aquatorial forests).

world_c1_af = world_c1.query("`Area` == 'Africa'")
fig1_c1_af = px.bar(data_frame=world_c1_af, x='Value', y='Item', animation_frame='Year', animation_group='Item', color='Item', range_x=[0, 1.2e6])
fig1_c1_af.show()
#Analysis of natural coverage in Oceania
Oceania is usually covered in shrubs, which highlights it a lot in comparison to other grafs. 🍃

world_c1_oc = world_c1.query("`Area` == 'Oceania'")
fig1_c1_oc = px.bar(data_frame=world_c1_oc, x='Value', y='Item', animation_frame='Year', animation_group='Item', color='Item', range_x=[0, 5e5])
fig1_c1_oc.show()

# This function takes two tables and their factoral column name and checks if values of first table`s column
# are substring of second and if values of second table`s column are substring of first. If yes, it changes value
# in the second table so that it would have analogical in first. It is gonna be used many times as we are working with
# different tables containing country names, which do not correspond always.

def equal_vals(tab1, tab2, col: str) -> None:
    try:
        vals1 = list(tab1[col])
        vals2 = list(tab2[col])
    except KeyError:
        raise KeyError('Column is not in table.')
    else:
        nocorr = set()
        for k, i in enumerate(vals2):
            if not isinstance(i, str):
                raise TypeError('Function is only applied to factoral columns')
            if i not in vals1:
                for j in vals1:
                    if not isinstance(j, str):
                        raise TypeError('Function is only applied to factoral columns')
                    if (i in j) or (j in i):
                        vals2[k] = j
                        break
                else:
                    nocorr.add(i)

        tab2[col] = pd.Series(vals2)
        print(f'No corresponding for some reason have: \n{nocorr}') # this function may not work properly always, but it prints the values which were not
                                                                  #changed so we could know what values are needed to be changed in code soon.


#This function takes a data frame , it`s column name, apropriate year and label to create a choropleth
#using also additional data frames with country codes etc. Make sure that column containing country
#names in all additional tables is named 'Area' before using.

def create_choropleth(data_frame, column: str, year: int, label: str, *adds) -> None:
    data = data_frame.query(f"`Year` == {year}")
    for i in adds:
        data = data.merge(i, on='Area')
    fig = px.choropleth(data, color=data[column], locations=data['Alpha-3 code'], labels={column: label}, hover_name=column, projection = "mollweide")
    fig.show()

def transform_to_percentage(data_frame, trans_column: str, new_col_name: str = 'new'): pass
equal_vals(area_burned, codes, 'Area')
create_choropleth(area_burned, 'Value', 2001, 'Area burned in 2001', codes)
create_choropleth(area_burned, 'Value', 2006, 'Area burned in 2006', codes)
create_choropleth(area_burned, 'Value', 2011, 'Area burned in 2011', codes)
create_choropleth(area_burned, 'Value', 2016, 'Area burned in 2016', codes)
create_choropleth(area_burned, 'Value', 2021, 'Area burned in 2021', codes)

def generalize(table, by: str, title: str, *countries):
    frame = table.copy(deep=True).query(f"Area in {str(list(countries))}")
    new_plot = px.line(data_frame=frame, x='Year', y=by, markers=True, color='Area')
    new_plot.show()

generalize(area_burned, 'Value', 'Area burned each year', *list(area_burned.copy(deep=True).sort_values(by='Value', ascending=False).iloc[0:38, 0]))

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

data = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ansstey/fires/main/co2_emission.csv")

years = [2001, 2006, 2011, 2016, 2021]
ghg_data = data[(data['Year'].isin(years)) & (data['Element'].isin(['Emissions (CO2)', 'Emissions (N2O)', 'Emissions (CH4)']))]

fig = px.choropleth(ghg_data,
                    locations="Area",
                    locationmode="country names",
                    color="Value",
                    hover_name="Area",
                    color_continuous_scale="Viridis",
                    title="Gas emissions in world",

                    animation_frame="Year",
                    facet_col="Element",
                    facet_col_wrap=3,
                    range_color=(0, ghg_data['Value'].max()))
fig.show()
**Nejaké vysledky s tohto**

co2_data = data[data['Element'] == 'Emissions (CO2)']
top_countries_co2 = co2_data.groupby('Area')['Value'].sum().reset_index()
